Returns the actions as a String. This is abstract so subclasses can defer creating a String representation until one is needed. Subclasses should always return actions in what they consider to be their canonical form. For example, two FilePermission objects created via the following:    perm1 = new FilePermission(p1,"read,write");
   perm2 = new FilePermission(p2,"write,read");
 both return "read,write" when the getActions method is invoked.
